{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e8346a9e-4bbf-4779-8e6d-790ae6016421","content":"Use **`Directory.Build.targets`** (not `.props`) and condition on `$(IsTestProject)`, which the test SDK sets automatically:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Directory.Build.targets -->\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup Condition=\"'$(IsTestProject)' == 'true'\">\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <EnableMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner>true</EnableMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Why `.targets` instead of `.props`?**  \n`IsTestProject` is set by the `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` NuGet package props, which are imported *after* `Directory.Build.props` but *before* `Directory.Build.targets`. So the property isn't available yet in `.props`.\n\n**Import order:**  \n`Directory.Build.props` → NuGet `.props` (sets `IsTestProject`) → project file → NuGet `.targets` → **`Directory.Build.targets`** ✅\n\nThis way `MyApp.csproj` stays a library and `MyApp.Tests.csproj` (which references `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk`) gets the MTP runner properties automatically — no naming conventions required.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"90996160-cca4-4aae-bda3-8122a3953d44","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to conditionally set MSBuild properties in a `Directory.Build.props` file so they only apply to test projects (not production/library projects) when migrating from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP).\n\nThis is a knowledge question — no codebase exploration needed.\n\nThe standard approach is to use an MSBuild condition that checks for the presence of a test-related package reference or a naming convention. The most robust way is to use `Condition=\"'$(IsTestProject)' == 'true'\"` which MSTest SDK sets automatically, or to match on project name convention.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach for MSTest + MTP migration:\n\n\nThe `IsTestProject` property gets set by the MSTest SDK, but it happens after `Directory.Build.props` is imported, so that file runs too early to use it. Instead, I should use `Directory.Build.targets` which evaluates later in the build process, or check for the MSTest package reference directly with a condition that looks for the NuGet package. would be available in `Directory.Build.targets` but not in `Directory.Build.props` due to the import order. For the MTP migration, I need to set `OutputType` to `Exe`, enable the testing platform runner, and configure dotnet test support. The most practical approach is using `Directory.Build.targets` with a condition on `IsTestProject` to apply these settings automatically to test projects.\n\nWriting configuration XML... Properties in targets files override project-level settings, so if I condition on `IsTestProject`, the targets approach would reliably set `OutputType` to `Exe` for test projects even if they explicitly set it otherwise — which is probably what we want for the MTP migration. I think using `Directory.Build.targets` with the `IsTestProject` condition is the cleanest path forward.","outputTokens":1423,"requestId":"5C38:19AB05:DEE89:114429:69F54C4D"},"id":"9ef2ab6b-6c16-4b1a-b428-28c943a2c7e2","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:59:23.148Z","parentId":"3f541eea-5cdc-474a-ad66-cb4e8df92e6e"}
